facts_and_links: {'Trivia': ['Some of the opening drone shots in the film showing shark nets on the Gold Coast, actually feature a barely visible baby humpback whale entangled in the net. The crew were there to get drone shots of the nets, but then spotted an entangled whale in the net and notified authorities and rescue teams. Authorities took hours to arrive and a good Samaritan ended up freeing the whale before their arrival. Known only as Django, he gained global news coverage and became dubbed "tinny man", named after the small boat he used for the rescue. The film crew documented the entire rescue, but it does not feature in the film.', 'https://www.imdb.com/title/tt12181374/trivia/?ref_=tt_dyk_trv']}

facts_and_links: {'Trivia': ['The logistics of getting camera equipment into such a location and filming in total darkness was just one of the challenges in making 20,000 Meters Under the Earth. Filming was also on hold for years following an incident in which one of the researchers was injured in a rock fall of 1000 meters. The incredible rescue operation involved more than 700 volunteers from Germany, Austria, Switzerland, Italy and Croatia lasted 11 days and was watched by millions of people on TV and the Internet. Not only did Johann Westhauser make a full recovery, he went on to rejoin the team and be part of this film production.', 'https://www.imdb.com/title/tt14967628/trivia/?ref_=tt_dyk_trv']}
